<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-353-010  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 353 010.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  June 7 1989 n1464 p43(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Performing for pay in computing. (employee rewards in UK computerindustry)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pancucci, Dom.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The computer industry is far ahead of other industries in Britainin adopting performance-related pay (PRP) as an employeeincentive.andP;  Under a PRP system, employees are rewarded forperformance with a comprehensive system of merit increases.andP;  IBMuses a worldwide PRP system with five merit ratings which measureachieved performance against set objectives.andP;  DEC, ICL and Unisysare among other firms operating in the UK which use PRP.andP;  Analystssee the development of PRP schemes as a response to the recessionin the high-tech business and skills shortages.andP;  Motivation ofemployees is a key factor in determining competitiveness, but canbackfire if a slump in overall business occurs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer IndustryEmployee RelationsSalaryPerformancePersonnel Management.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>